Second Lady Karen Pence, accompanied by Deputy Secretary of Interior Katharine MacGregor, visited Rocky Mountain National Park to highlight the mental health benefits of the outdoors and the important work of National Park Service employees as the parks reopen. They received a briefing on the park's employee health and wellness program, which aims to promote resilience and address issues such as stress. Mrs. Pence delivered remarks at the park, emphasizing the positive health benefits of spending time in nature. She then traveled to the Marcus Institute for Brain Health to highlight PTSD Awareness Day and led a roundtable discussion on the healing power of art therapy for veterans. Mrs. Pence is the Lead Ambassador for PREVENTS, an interagency task force that focuses on empowering veterans and preventing suicide. PREVENTS launched a public health awareness campaign called "More Than Ever Before" to help people cope with the stress and anxiety caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.